          {
            "@type": "@builder.io/sdk:Element",
            "@version": 2,
            "id": "builder-66ca28ef657e4469a78976eaedb1ae18",
            "meta": {
              "previousId": "builder-24a9aaabb7d4434ba586b2d574f14379",
              "localizedTextInputs": ["rawHtml"]
            },
            "component": {
              "name": "Copy",
              "options": {
                "rawHtml": "<p>\n  Then, how do EOA and CA correspond to Solana's Account structure? They can be\n  mapped as follows.\n</p>\n"
              }
            },
            "responsiveStyles": {
              "large": {
                "display": "flex",
                "flexDirection": "column",
                "position": "relative",
                "flexShrink": "0",
                "boxSizing": "border-box",
                "paddingTop": "20px"
              }
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "@builder.io/sdk:Element",
            "@version": 2,
            "id": "builder-24a9aaabb7d4434ba586b2d574f14379",
            "meta": {
              "previousId": "builder-1f66a65b077c4b4ea6a7270e326cd19a"
            },
            "component": {
              "name": "Copy",
              "options": {
                "rawHtml": "<p><strong>EOA (Externally Owned Account, Wallet) </strong></p><ul><li>→ non-executable, data accounts</li><li>However, individual wallets on Solana are composed of a collection of <strong>data accounts,</strong> which are a broader concept than <strong>EOA.</strong></li></ul><p><strong>CA (Contract Account)</strong></p><ul><li>→ executable, program accounts</li><li>While sharing the same concept, Ethereum's <strong>CA</strong> cannot execute transactions on their own; they must be executed by <strong>EOA.</strong></li></ul>"
              }
            },
